dum: dummare, 1) Only used, optionally, to refer to things whose natural gender is masculine.2) The indefinite superlative forms are only used in the predicative.3) Dated or archaic, dumme, ndum, dummeste, 1) When an adjective is applied predicatively to something definite, the corresponding "indefinite" form is used. 2) The "indefinite" superlatives may not be used attributively., dumpronounced with /ð(ʲ)-/, Note: Some of these forms may be hypothetical. Not everypossible mutated form of every word actually occurs., dummest2, dum, dummere, dummast, dummaste, dumt, dumma

2re: 
diviti: divite, bȕdēte divili2, divio je2, divljasmo, divit će1diviće, bȉo bih divio2, bíli biste divili2, bíli su divili2, 1   Croatian spelling: others omit the infinitive suffix completely and bind the clitic.2   For masculine nouns; a feminine or neuter agent would use the feminine and neuter gender forms of the active past participle and auxiliary verb, respectively.3   Often replaced by the past perfect in colloquial speech, i.e. the auxiliary verb biti (to be) is routinely dropped.
4   Often replaced by the conditional I in colloquial speech, i.e. the auxiliary verb biti (to be) is routinely dropped.
  * Note: The aorist and imperfect have nowadays fallen into disuse in many dialects and therefore they are routinely replaced by the past perfect in both formal and colloquial speech., divit ćeš1divićeš, divim, divio bi2, divili su2, divljaše, bíli smo divili2, divit ćete1divićete, divit ću1diviću, bȕdē divio2, bȉo si divio2, bíli bismo divili2, diviš, divit ćemo1divićemo, bíli ste divili2, bȕdēm divio2, divljah, —, divljahu, bȕdēmo divili2, divili m / divile f / divila n, dive, divio si2, divljaste, Imperfect, divili bismo2, bíli bi divili2, divili ste2, divili biste2, divili smo2, divio bih2, divili bi2, Future I, divio m / divila f / divilo n, divi, bȉo bi divio2, bȉo sam divio2, divio sam2, divimo, bȕdēš divio2, bȕdū divili2, bȉo je divio2

pluperfect subjunctive → past subjunctive

imperfect subjunctive → present subjunctive
pluperfect subjunctive → past subjunctive

miser: , miseraient/miz.ʁɛ/, miserum, miseram, misassiez/mi.za.sje/, misasses/mi.zas/, misassent/mi.zas/, misèrent/mi.zɛʁ/, miserōrum, misâmes/mi.zam/, miseras/miz.ʁa/, misera/miz.ʁa/, misions/mi.zjɔ̃/, miserō, miserīs, miserī, misais/mi.zɛ/, mises/miz/, miserez/miz.ʁe/, miseront/miz.ʁɔ̃/, miserais/miz.ʁɛ/, misât/mi.za/, misassions/mi.za.sjɔ̃/, miserae, misez/mi.ze/, misas/mi.za/, 1 The French gerund is usable only with the preposition en., misaient/mi.zɛ/, miserons/miz.ʁɔ̃/, —, misiez/mi.zje/, misai/mi.ze/, miserai/miz.ʁe/, misant/mi.zɑ̃/, miserions/mi.zə.ʁjɔ̃/, misera, miser, miserōs, misé/mi.ze/, misâtes/mi.zat/, miserā, 2 In less formal writing or speech, these tenses may be found to have been replaced in the following way:
past historic → present perfect
past anterior → pluperfect
imperfect subjunctive → present subjunctive
pluperfect subjunctive → past subjunctive
(Christopher Kendris [1995], Master the Basics: French, pp. 77, 78, 79, 81)., miserās, misons/mi.zɔ̃/, miserait/miz.ʁɛ/, miseriez/mi.zə.ʁje/, misasse/mi.zas/, miserārum, misait/mi.zɛ/, mise/miz/, misent/miz/, misa/mi.za/

latent: eine latente, latentul, 1) Only used, optionally, to refer to things whose natural gender is masculine.2) The indefinite superlative forms are only used in the predicative.3) Dated or archaic, latenta, (keine) latenten, einer latenten, einen latenten, latentei, einem latenten, latenților, latent, die latenten, latentem, latente, die latente, (keinen) latenten, latenții, latentelor, ein latentes, 1) When an adjective is applied predicatively to something definite, the corresponding "indefinite" form is used. 2) The "indefinite" superlatives may not be used attributively., —, er ist latent, den latenten, —2, des latenten, latentes, der latenten, sie ist latent, latentului, latenter, ein latenter, latentele, der latente, es ist latent, dem latenten, sie sind latent, das latente, eines latenten, latentă, latenți, (keiner) latenten, latenten

computer: , computernes, computassiez/kɔ̃.py.ta.sje/, computeras/kɔ̃.py.tʁa/, computassions/kɔ̃.py.ta.sjɔ̃/, computerne, computerai/kɔ̃.py.tʁe/, (unui) computer, computerait/kɔ̃.py.tʁɛ/, computerului, computerons/kɔ̃.py.tʁɔ̃/, computions/kɔ̃.py.tjɔ̃/, computeront/kɔ̃.py.tʁɔ̃/, computerelor, computera/kɔ̃.py.tʁa/, computât/kɔ̃.py.ta/, computent/kɔ̃.pyt/, compute/kɔ̃.pyt/, computerions/kɔ̃.py.tə.ʁjɔ̃/, computerez/kɔ̃.py.tʁe/, computai/kɔ̃.py.te/, computâmes/kɔ̃.py.tam/, computerais/kɔ̃.py.tʁɛ/, computez/kɔ̃.py.te/, computeriez/kɔ̃.py.tə.ʁje/, computers, computons/kɔ̃.py.tɔ̃/, computere, (unor) computere, (niște) computere, computerens, computant/kɔ̃.py.tɑ̃/, computèrent/kɔ̃.py.tɛʁ/, computasses/kɔ̃.py.tas/, computiez/kɔ̃.py.tje/, 1 The French gerund is usable only with the preposition en., computaient/kɔ̃.py.tɛ/, (un) computer, computeraient/kɔ̃.py.tʁɛ/, computais/kɔ̃.py.tɛ/, —, computeren, computassent/kɔ̃.py.tas/, computerul, computes/kɔ̃.pyt/, computerele, computait/kɔ̃.py.tɛ/, computas/kɔ̃.py.ta/, computerule, computâtes/kɔ̃.py.tat/, 2 In less formal writing or speech, these tenses may be found to have been replaced in the following way:
past historic → present perfect
past anterior → pluperfect
imperfect subjunctive → present subjunctive
pluperfect subjunctive → past subjunctive
(Christopher Kendris [1995], Master the Basics: French, pp. 77, 78, 79, 81)., computer, computé/kɔ̃.py.te/, computa/kɔ̃.py.ta/, computeres, computasse/kɔ̃.py.tas/

munda: , mungaha, að munda, munin, munda, munmaspäi, munižiba, mundaðrar, þú mundaðist, mundud, munižit, muniži, 1 In imperative: used only in the second-person singular. The plural form is used with other persons., munnu, munib, muni, þið munduðust, ég mundist, munduðu, munnen, mundandist ** ** the mediopassive present participle is extremely rare and normally not used; it is never used attributively or predicatively, only for explicatory subclauses, mundast (þú), mungoi, ég mundaðist, munim, munind, mundaða, munnuiži, mundes, þú mundar, ég mundaði, munmas, munižin, —, að mundast, mundist (þið), munneba, ég munda, munnuižit, við mundum, mungam, mundandi, þið mundist, mundisti *, munižid, muniba, mundaðu, mundið (þið), munit, mundastu, munmaha, mundaði, munii, munda (þú), mundaðan, munden, munmal, við munduðumst, munid, ég mundast, hann, hún, það mundaðist, munnuižin, munned, þið munduðuð, munmat, * Spoken form, usually not written; in writing, the unappended plural form (optionally followed by the full pronoun) is preferred., mungat, mundaðra, hann, hún, það mundi, hann, hún, það mundar, þú mundast, munduð, þú mundir, munnem, hann, hún, það mundaði, við mundumst, þú mundist, mundaðar, þið mundið, mundaður, mundaðri, mundaðs, munižim, mundast, mundað, munduðum, munne, þeir, þær, þau mundist, ég mundi, munneb, þeir, þær, þau munduðu, mundasmuniba, munnet, munnuižim, munnuižiba, hann, hún, það mundist, þeir, þær, þau munduðust, munnuižid, við munduðum, þeir, þær, þau munda, munnugoi, mundiði *, mundaðir, þeir, þær, þau mundast, hann, hún, það mundast, þú mundaðir, þeir, þær, þau mundi

past anterior → pluperfect
imperfect subjunctive → present subjunctive
pluperfect subjunctive → past subjunctive

mariti: bíli smo marili2, marili m / marile f / marila n, mariš, bȉo sam mario2, marah, bȕdū marili2, mario bi2, marili smo2, bíli bismo marili2, bȕdēmo marili2, marasmo, bíli biste marili2, marili bismo2, 1   Croatian spelling: others omit the infinitive suffix completely and bind the clitic.2   For masculine nouns; a feminine or neuter agent would use the feminine and neuter gender forms of the active past participle and auxiliary verb, respectively.3   Often replaced by the past perfect in colloquial speech, i.e. the auxiliary verb biti (to be) is routinely dropped.
4   Often replaced by the conditional I in colloquial speech, i.e. the auxiliary verb biti (to be) is routinely dropped.

ite: , iñeitɨkaɨ, iñedomoɨ, iñeitɨkue, iitaɨmaiaɨ, itɨkaɨ, ina, iñeitaɨmaiaɨ, iñedɨkaɨ, iitɨkoko, iga, ieten, iño!, iitɨkaɨñaɨ, iitomɨñoɨ, iñeitomoɨ, iñeitomɨko, itɨkaɨñaɨ, itɨmakɨ, iñeite, iten n, iñeitɨñaiño, ntolu, ntelu, n, itolu, itelu, y, iñedaɨmaiaɨ, ia, h-ite, iñeitɨmakɨ, iñedɨkaɨñaɨ, itaɨñuaɨ, ate, a, itomɨñoɨ, itomɨko, iza!, ietst, iñeno!, itɨñaiño, iñedɨñaiño, ikana, ino, itomoɨ, iten, iitɨmakɨ, iitomɨko, iñedomɨko, iitomoɨ, iñeitɨkoko, iyɨ, iñedomɨñoɨ, iitɨñaiño, iñeitomɨñoɨ, iñeyɨ, yt, iitɨmɨe, iñeitɨmɨe, iñeitaɨñuaɨ, iye, t-ite, not applicable, iñede, 1) The animate 3rd singular inflections are only used when the animacy of the subject needs to be emphasised. Otherwise, the neutral 3rd singular is used.*) Deverbal nominals can be obtained also by adding nominal classifiers directly to the stem.**) Same-time forms may be formed from any indicative form by adding the ending -mo directly to the inflected form.***) The evidentiality markers -dɨ, -za and -ta may be added to any indicative form., iñedo, ytst, itɨkue, iñedɨmakɨ, iñedɨkoko, altolu, altelu, al, iite, iñedaɨñuaɨ, ikaina, iitɨkaɨ, ita, hawwe, iñeito, iñega, iñokai!, itɨmɨe, iitɨkue, hite, itɨkoko, nte, n, m, iñedɨkue, ito, ite, iitaɨñuaɨ, itend, ite, i, iito, iet, Note: Some of these forms may be hypothetical. dire: , dirai, dirà, dìci, dites/dit/, dissiez/di.sje/, dirèbbe, dirébbe, dîmes/dim/, dicévano, dicésti, dit, dirèi, dirons, disons/di.zɔ̃/, dìssi, disaient/di.zɛ/, dirait/di.ʁɛ/, dìcono, non dìre, en disant, diroit, direit, desissons, desissiens, dìca, diiens, dions, disiens, disons, détto, dise/diz/, dicémmo, desissent, disoient, diseient, 2 In less formal writing or speech, these tenses may be found to have been replaced in the following way:
past historic → present perfect
past anterior → pluperfect
imperfect subjunctive → present subjunctive
pluperfect subjunctive → past subjunctive
(Christopher Kendris [1995], Master the Basics: French, pp. 77, 78, 79, 81)., disent/diz/, non dìca, diiez, disiez, non dìcano, desisses, disiez/di.zje/, dît/di/, dì', dì1,2, dirài, avére, dicévo, diront/di.ʁɔ̃/, desistes, dirémo, di, dìte, desisse, —, dicéste, dira/di.ʁa/, disant/di.zɑ̃/, dicevàmo, dïe, dìre, dìsse, dicéssimo, dirò, disait/di.zɛ/, dis/di/, dirais/di.ʁɛ/, disant, dirons/di.ʁɔ̃/, dicévi, desimes, dira, diciàte, non dìte, dicènte, disais/di.zɛ/, dicésse, dicèndo, dirànno, dis, diciàmo, dire, diroient, direient, diréte, 1 The French gerund is usable only with the preposition en., disions/di.zjɔ̃/, dirèbbero, dirébbero, Use the gerund of avoir followed by the past participle, dites, dissions/di.sjɔ̃/, non diciàmo, diroiz, direiz, direz, dîtes/dit/, dissent/dis/, diriiez, diriez, diraient/di.ʁɛ/, dirent/diʁ/, diriez/di.ʁje/, dicevàte, diriiens, diriens, dit/di/, diréste, desis, dïes, avoir dit, disoies, diseies, dimes, dions, disons, disses/dis/, dist, diroies, direies, disse/dis/, dient, dirémmo, direz/di.ʁe/, diras/di.ʁa/, dirions/di.ʁjɔ̃/, dìcano, dirai/di.ʁe/, distrent, disiiens, disiens, diras, dïent, dicéva, dirésti, dises/diz/, dìco, dicéssi, disiiez, disiez, diroie, direie, desissoiz, desissez, desissiez, disoie, diseie, disoit, diseit, desist, diront, dìssero, dicéssero, dìce

diligenter: diligentiez/di.li.ʒɑ̃.tje/, diligentez/di.li.ʒɑ̃.te/, diligentons/di.li.ʒɑ̃.tɔ̃/, diligenteriez/di.li.ʒɑ̃.tə.ʁje/, diligenteras/di.li.ʒɑ̃.tʁa/, diligentait/di.li.ʒɑ̃.tɛ/, diligenterons/di.li.ʒɑ̃.tʁɔ̃/, diligentèrent/di.li.ʒɑ̃.tɛʁ/, diligenterai/di.li.ʒɑ̃.tʁe/, diligenterions/di.li.ʒɑ̃.tə.ʁjɔ̃/, diligentais/di.li.ʒɑ̃.tɛ/, diligentasses/di.li.ʒɑ̃.tas/, diligenteront/di.li.ʒɑ̃.tʁɔ̃/, diligentasse/di.li.ʒɑ̃.tas/, diligenteraient/di.li.ʒɑ̃.tʁɛ/, diligentaient/di.li.ʒɑ̃.tɛ/, diligentant/di.li.ʒɑ̃.tɑ̃/, diligenterez/di.li.ʒɑ̃.tʁe/, diligentassions/di.li.ʒɑ̃.ta.sjɔ̃/, diligentions/di.li.ʒɑ̃.tjɔ̃/, 1 The French gerund is usable only with the preposition en., diligentassent/di.li.ʒɑ̃.tas/, —, diligentent/di.li.ʒɑ̃t/, diligentera/di.li.ʒɑ̃.tʁa/, diligenterais/di.li.ʒɑ̃.tʁɛ/, diligentas/di.li.ʒɑ̃.ta/, diligentâtes/di.li.ʒɑ̃.tat/, diligentai/di.li.ʒɑ̃.te/, diligenté/di.li.ʒɑ̃.te/, diligenter, diligente/di.li.ʒɑ̃t/, diligentâmes/di.li.ʒɑ̃.tam/, diligenta/di.li.ʒɑ̃.ta/, diligentassiez/di.li.ʒɑ̃.ta.sje/, 2 In less formal writing or speech, these tenses may be found to have been replaced in the following way:
past historic → present perfect
past anterior → pluperfect
imperfect subjunctive → present subjunctive
pluperfect subjunctive → past subjunctive
(Christopher Kendris [1995], Master the Basics: French, pp. 77, 78, 79, 81)., diligentât/di.li.ʒɑ̃.ta/, diligenterait/di.li.ʒɑ̃.tʁɛ/, diligentes/di.li.ʒɑ̃t/

velim: velili bi2, bȉo bi velio2, velili biste2, velio si2, veljah, bíli bi velili2, bíli su velili2, 1   Croatian spelling: others omit the infinitive suffix completely and bind the clitic.2   For masculine nouns; a feminine or neuter agent would use the feminine and neuter gender forms of the active past participle and auxiliary verb, respectively.3   Often replaced by the past perfect in colloquial speech, i.e. the auxiliary verb biti (to be) is routinely dropped.
4   Often replaced by the conditional I in colloquial speech, i.e. the auxiliary verb biti (to be) is routinely dropped.
  * Note: The aorist and imperfect have nowadays fallen into disuse in many dialects and therefore they are routinely replaced by the past perfect in both formal and colloquial speech., velim / velju, velimo, velio bih2, bȕdēm velio2, bȕdēš velio2, velite, bȕdēte velili2, bȕdē velio2, velio m / velila f / velilo n, bȉo sam velio2, bȉo bih velio2, vele, bȕdēmo velili2, velili smo2, veljaše, velili ste2, velio bi2, —, veliš, velio sam2, bȕdū velili2, bȉo je velio2, veljahu, bíli bismo velili2, bíli ste velili2, velili su2, veli, Imperfect, veljasmo, velili m / velile f / velila n, bíli biste velili2, veljaste, bȉo si velio2, bíli smo velili2, velili bismo2, velio je2

citer: , citrōrum, citassions/si.ta.sjɔ̃/, citassiez/si.ta.sje/, citrō, citâtes/si.tat/, citas/si.ta/, citerons/si.tʁɔ̃/, citrum, citent/sit/, citassent/si.tas/, citons/si.tɔ̃/, citerens, cites/sit/, citeren, citeriez/si.tə.ʁje/, citez/si.te/, citeront/si.tʁɔ̃/, citra, citrīs, citait/si.tɛ/, citions/si.tjɔ̃/, citrā, cita/si.ta/, citrae, citâmes/si.tam/, citiez/si.tje/, citera/si.tʁa/, citasse/si.tas/, 1 The French gerund is usable only with the preposition en., citât/si.ta/, —, citerecitre, cite/sit/, citèrent/si.tɛʁ/, citerions/si.tə.ʁjɔ̃/, cité/si.te/, citerait/si.tʁɛ/, citeras/si.tʁa/, citasses/si.tas/, citernescitrenes, citeraient/si.tʁɛ/, citram, 2 In less formal writing or speech, these tenses may be found to have been replaced in the following way:
past historic → present perfect
past anterior → pluperfect
imperfect subjunctive → present subjunctive
pluperfect subjunctive → past subjunctive
(Christopher Kendris [1995], Master the Basics: French, pp. 77, 78, 79, 81)., citerescitres, citant/si.tɑ̃/, citernecitrene, citais/si.tɛ/, citai/si.te/, citaient/si.tɛ/, citerai/si.tʁe/, citrī, citrās, citrārum, citrōs, citers, citer, citerais/si.tʁɛ/, citerez/si.tʁe/

past historic → present perfect
past anterior → pluperfect
imperfect subjunctive → present subjunctive
pluperfect subjunctive → past subjunctive
